The 1957 event, attended by Senator [[John F. Kennedy]], his wife, [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis|Jackie]], and [[Marilyn Monroe]], included 1300 guests, who paid $100 each and donated $130,000 to charities;{{sfn|Time Inc|1957|p=201}} the Duke and Duchess of Windsor attended as well.{{sfn|King|2011|p=427}} The Duchess and Elsa Maxwell had reportedly had a major falling out at another ball four years earlier and sat far apart from each other and didn't speak even when they were in the elevator together.<ref>{{cite news|title="Sick of all deformed gals", says Lauren Bacall, "Who isn't"?|url=
https://www.newspapers.com/clip/1590577/duchess_and_elsa_maxwell_in_same/|newspaper=[[The Raleigh Register]]|date=18 April 1957|page=4|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|location=Beckley, West Virginia}} 
{{Open access}}</ref> The Duke and Duchess were the guests of honor and were seated at the most visible table in the ballroom.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/1593797/elsa_marilyn_steal_thunder_from_duchess/|title=Elsa, Marilyn Steal Thunder From Duchess|page=1|date=12 April 1957|newspaper=The Lawton Constitution|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|location=Lawton, Oaklahoma}} 
{{Open access}}</ref>   One article in '' The Times Standard'' even claimed that Maxwell had invited Monroe to the ball to publicly embarrass the Duchess; when Monroe arrived more than 30 photographer abandoned her to photograph Monroe.<ref>{{cite news|title=Elsa Maxwell Uses Marilyn Monroe to Embarrass Duchess |url=
https://www.newspapers.com/clip/1590316/elsa_maxwell_uses_marilyn_monroe_to/
|newspaper=[[The Times Standard]]|date=12 April 1957|page=1|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|location=Eureka, California}} 
{{Open access}}</ref> After the ball, a wealthy New York broker offered to donate $50,000 to charity if Maxwell and the Duchess would abandon their feud and shake hands in front of press photographers.  Maxwell was most willing to end the quarrel in this way, but the Duchess declined the offer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1301&dat=19570414&id=UnZWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xeQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5512,3496555|title=Cash Can't Heal Feud|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|page=1|date=14 April 1957|location=Sydney, Australia}}</ref> The following year, the ballroom was decorated with {{convert|30|ft}} high chestnut trees. The event brought in US$170,000 for charities.{{sfn|Time Inc|1958|p=137}}

===1959===
[[File:Marlene Dietrich April in Paris Ball 1959.jpg|thumb|250px|Dietrich at the April in Paris Ball in 1959]]
The 1959 ball, the final one to be held at the Waldorf on 10 April 1959, centred around the theme of the Parisian circus of the 18th century. 1000 people attended, paying $150 per ticket.<ref name="NH">{{cite news|title=Dietrich Makes Singing Debut at Society Circus|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/1591418/marlene_dietrich_at_april_in_paris_ball/|newspaper=[[The News-Herald (Franklin, Pennsylvania)|The News-Herald]]|date=11 April 1959|page=1|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|location=Franklin, Pennsylvania }} 
{{Open access}}</ref> Genuine circus costumes from the period were flown over from France, and the ball featured [[Marlene Dietrich]] as a ringmaster in trousers, a waistcoat, top hat and white gloves.{{sfn|Morehouse III|1991|p=230}} Dietrich sang two Maurice Chevalier songs, "Louise" and "Mimi". Cecil Beaton designed a big top of ruby velvet with a "hedge of colored fountains" and thousands of purple flowers.<ref name="NH"/>

===1960===
Due to conflict between Philippe and the Waldorf-Astoria staff, he was exiled from the Waldorf in 1960, and the ball was moved to the Hotel Astor that year, where the likes of Dietrich, [[Maurice Chevalier]], [[Joan Crawford]] and organizer Elsa Maxwell helped transform it into the [[Paris Opera House]].{{sfn|Morehouse III|1991|p=231}}  A photomural of the Paris Opera House was "mounted on plywood and superimposed in front of Astor Hotel creating the illusion of [the] actual opera house", and photomurals of the interior completed the transformation.{{sfn|Morehouse III|1991|p=235}} Held on 9 April 1960 under the title of ''Un Bal Masque a l'Opéra de Paris'', the show featured a series of tableaux entitled ''L'Elegance de Paris'', with costumes by [[Revillon]], ''La Couture'', with designs by [[Pierre Cardin]], Jean Desses, [[Christian Dior]], Gres, [[Jacques Heim]], [[Hermès]], [[Guy LaRoche]], Nina Ricci and Jean Patou, ''La Couleur Opera'', featuring "La Cabaret de l'Aurore" and the [[Lester Lanin]] orchestra and the US premiere of the 1735 [[Jean-Philippe Rameau]] French opera-ballet "[[Les Indes Galantes]]", starring [[Mony Dalmes]], [[Jean-Pierre Aumont]] and [[Jean Jacques Strauss]], ''Les Fleurs'', with Parisian and European opera and ballet stars such as [[Claude Besny]], [[Pierre LaCotte]], [[George Zoritch]], [[Judith Raskin]], and [[Madeleine Rizzo]], and finally ''Les Savages & La Chaconne'', featuring [[Cathryn Damon]], [[Dorothy Straiger]], [[Constance Carpenter]], [[Gretchen Wyler]], [[Charlton Heston]] and [[Myles Easton]].{{sfn|Morehouse III|1991|pp=232-3}}

===Later balls===
Several ball committee members felt that the name of the ball should be changed, since it was no longer held in April, but in the fall.  In 1968, the ball's name was changed to Bal de l'Amitie.  The new name lasted only one year and it once more became known as the April in Paris ball in 1969.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/06/04/archives/its-the-april-in-paris-ball-again-after-a-year-as-bal-de-lamitie.html|title=It's the April in Paris Ball Again After a Year as Bal de l'Amitie|date=4 June 1969|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=27 January 2014}} (subscription required)</ref> [[Moune de Rival]] was invited to the 1970 event,{{sfn|Johnson Publishing Company|1970|p=44}} while in 1973, [[Josephine Baker]] was its star.{{sfn|Baker|Chase|2001|p=460}} [[Russell Edwards]] of ''The New York Times'' stated that even in 1974 the Paris Ball "remains the most prestigious, with its national and international guest list, but not necessarily the most social".<ref>{{cite news|title=Charity Balls|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/55910079/?terms=Waldorf+Astoria|newspaper=[[Kansas City Star]]|date=10 February 1974|page=76|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|location=Kansas City, Missouri}} 
{{Open access}}</ref>

