'''The Sydney Fringe''' is an alternative arts and culture festival held for the first time in September 2010 in the [[Inner West|inner west]] of [[Sydney]], Australia. 

The Fringe is an initiative of the [[Newtown, New South Wales|Newtown]] Entertainment Precinct Association.<ref name=NEPA>[http://thesydneyfringe.com.au/about The Sydney Fringe - About Us], Accessed 15/2/10</ref> It is the largest alternative visual and [[performing arts]] event in NSW. It encompasses genres such as [[stand-up comedy]], [[Concert|music]], [[theatre]], [[cabaret]], [[visual arts]], and [[burlesque]], though shows and events that are not easily labelled in that manner are highly encouraged; evidence of this in past years has included [[podcast]] recordings<ref>http://2012.sydneyfringe.com/event/comedy/minutes-podcast</ref><ref>http://2012.sydneyfringe.com/event/comedy/seizure-kaiser-film-chat-podcast</ref> and [[indie video game]] events.<ref>http://2012.sydneyfringe.com/event/special-events/brain-soup-indie-video-game-showcase</ref> It is billed as "a time for risk, discovery and adventure [...] a three week celebration of the strange and the beautiful."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnsw.com/2012/03/richard-hull-sydney-fringe-festival-director/|title=Richard Hull-Sydney Fringe Festival 2012|date=21 March 2012|website=musicnsw.com|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref>

The Sydney Fringe, began as a curated festival (like the [[New York International Fringe Festival]]) as opposed to an open access "unjuried" festival (the model used by the [[Edinburgh Fringe Festival]]).<ref name=SMH-2009-12-19>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/arts/newtown-gets-a-cuttingedge-fringe/2009/12/17/1260639252913.html?page=-1 Sydney Morning Herald 19/12/09 "Newtown gets a cutting-edge fringe"], Accessed 15/2/10</ref> In 2012, festival director Richard Hull implemented the open access festival model, whereby the visual arts is now the only curated element.<ref>http://2012.sydneyfringe.com/news/prepare-unleash-yourself</ref>

The Sydney Fringe typically operates in a festival precinct encompassing a number of venues in the [[Newtown, New South Wales|Newtown]]/[[Marrickville, New South Wales|Marrickville]]/[[Enmore, New South Wales|Enmore]] area, with a few other venues in the wider Sydney area, including Leichhardt, Parramatta, Oxford Street and the City.<ref name=SydneyFringeVenues>[http://2012.sydneyfringe.com/FAQ The Sydney Fringe - FAQs], Accessed 15/2/10</ref> In a departure from previous years, where venues registered with the Fringe in the same manner as artists, the Fringe 2013 team have selected a list of over 60 Sydney venues, for artists to then communicate and draw up contracts with.

==Previous Sydney Fringe Festivals==
A Sydney Fringe Festival ran from 1994 to 2002 in [[Bondi, New South Wales|Bondi]], founded by producer Megan Donnelly and [[Katrina Sedgwick]]. The Live Bait Festival, a successor to the Sydney Fringe Festival, also operated out of Bondi from 2003–2004 and was co-produced by Michael Cohen and Glenn Wright.<ref name=SMH-2006-01-24>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/arts/somethings-missing-on-the-edge-of-the-stage/2006/01/24/1138066794633.html Sydney Morning Herald 24/1/06 "Something's missing on the edge of the stage"], Accessed 15/2/10</ref>

