{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox UN resolution |number = 546 |organ = SC |date = 6 January |year = 1984 |meeting = 2,511 |code = S/RES/546 |document = https://undocs.org/S/RES/546(1984) |for = 13 |abstention = 2 |against = 0 |subject = Angola-South Africa |result = Adopted |image = South Africa Border War Map.png |caption = South African border operations }}
'''United Nations Security Council resolution 546''', adopted on 6 January 1984, after hearing representations from the [[People's Republic of Angola]], the Council recalled resolutions [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 387|387]] (1976), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 428|428]] (1978), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 447|447]] (1979), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 454|454]] (1979), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 475|475]] (1980) and [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 545|545]] (1983), and expressed its concern at the continuing attacks on the country by South Africa through occupied [[South West Africa]].
The Council demanded South Africa cease the attacks and respect Angola's sovereignty and territorial integrity, noting that Angola is entitled to the [[right of self-defense]] and to compensation for the attacks. It also called upon South Africa to cease the occupation of southern Angola and withdraw its forces. The resolution urged Member States to provide economic assistance to Angola, as well as enforce [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 418|Resolution 418]] (1977) on the [[arms embargo]] against South Africa. It also requested the [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary-General]] continue to monitor the situation and report back to the Council as appropriate.
The resolution was approved by 13 votes to none against, while the United Kingdom and United States [[abstention|abstained]] from voting.
